f̶̑i̸̓̄m̸͌s̸̍͝ḩ̸̎e̴̍̏ 🦖 2023-11-24 9:29 PM
Marlin— as in the colossal billfish— was meant to be named after the seafarer's tool, the "marlinspike"; a horn fashioned into a giant needle, used to cut, and make knots with marine rope. The rostrum (beak) of the fish resembled the tool. However, it only retained the "marlin" part of the name, which meant to "mar the line", or to cease the line. One of the main functions of the marlinspike was to retrieve a "ceasing string", by unwinding the rope— which was made out of multiple twined strings— and cutting one of the loose strands. The ceasing string was then used to tie off the end of a rope to prevent it from fraying. The word "mar" from "marring line", is traced back to the proto-indo-european word "mer-", which means "death". Overtime, the word simply referred to "ceasing" or "ending" something.
